                    <h2 id="RA_dbGaP"><strong>Requesting Access via dbGaP</strong></h2>
                    <h3><strong>Non-NIH Employees</strong></h3>
                    <p>For full and detailed instructions on how to request data access via dbGaP, please visit this <a href="https://grants.nih.gov/policy-and-compliance/policy-topics/sharing-policies/accessing-data/dbgap" target="_blank">Overview from the NIH Grants & Funding website</a>.</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Pre-Requisites for Requesting Data: There are several pre-requisites for requesting data via dbGaP, so please check that that you are:
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li>A permanent member of your institution and have an institutional email.</li>
                                <li>Either at a level equivalent to a tenure-track professor, or a senior scientist with responsibilities that may include laboratory or research program administration and oversight.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </li>
                        <li>Create credentials to submit a request through dbGaP
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li>You must have an <a href="https://era.nih.gov/register-accounts" target="_blank">eRA account</a> to submit requests through dbGaP.</li>
                                <li>Please use your institutional email address when creating an eRA account.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </li>
                        <li>Prepare the Data Request
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li>Visit the page for the dbGaP data you wish to request and click “Authorized Access.”</li>
                                <li>Log into the system using your eRA credentials.</li>
                                <li>Once you are logged in you will be able to view your research projects and ongoing requests.</li>
                                <li>Under “My Projects,” select “Create New Research Project.”</li>
                                <li>After reading the instructions and before you get started sections, select “Begin New Research Project.”</li>
                                <li>You can then search for HINTS data if you have not yet selected it.</li>
                                <li>Click the checkbox next to “General Research Use” under the HINTS dataset label and press “Add Selected and Continue.”</li>
                                <li>You will then fill out various sections of the submission form, which include project title, research use statement, non-technical summary, signing official, internal collaborators, and IT director.</li>
                                <li>You will review data use certifications, restrictions on use, limitations on use, and various other documentation, then submit your application.</li>
                                <li>Once a data request is submitted, it is routed to your institution’s SO for review, approval, and co-signature.</li>
                                <li>For tips on preparing a submission, please visit this <a href="https://grants.nih.gov/sites/default/files/flmngr/Tips for Preparing a Successful DAR.pdf" target="_blank">dbGaP Tip Sheet</a>. </li>
                            </ol>
                        </li>
                        <li>A Data Access Committee (DAC) Reviews the Request
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li>Each dataset has a DAC, a group of experts who review the request for compliance with NIH policy and the appropriateness of the request with respect to the dataset.</li>
                                <li>If a request is approved, you will receive an email with additional instructions on accessing the dataset.</li>
                                <li>If a request is denied, you can adjust the submission and re-submit. There are <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/n/helpdbgap/DAreq_ReviseAmndUpd/#DAreq_ReviseAmndUpd.Revise_Data_Access_R" target="_blank">specific steps for resubmission</a>.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </li>
                        <li>Accessing the Data
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li>If a data request is approved via dbGaP, you will be referred to NCI’s General Commons to then access the data.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </li>
                    </ol>



                    <h3><strong>NIH Employees</strong></h3>
                    <p>For full and detailed instructions on how to request data access via dbGaP, please visit the <a href="https://grants.nih.gov/sites/default/files/flmngr/NIH_Intramural_Request_Form_Final.pdf" target="_blank">NIH staff specific instructions</a>.</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Pre-Requisites for Requesting Data: There are several pre-requisites for requesting data via dbGaP:
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li>NIH Intramural Investigators: must be a tenure-track investigator, senior investigator, senior scientist, senior clinician, or staff scientist.</li>
                                <li>NIH Extramural Scientific Staff: must have administrative responsibility for the data; have substantial research involvement in the award that generated the data; or need access to carry out research unrelated to their portfolio management responsibilities.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </li>
                        <li>Get IC Permission to Request Data
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li>You must get permission from your IC prior to requesting data through dbGaP. This includes filling out the <a href="https://grants.nih.gov/sites/default/files/flmngr/NIH_Intramural_Request_Form_Final.pdf" target="_blank">Permission Form for NIH Staff Access to Controlled-Access Data in dbGaP</a> and submitting it to your IC’s signing official (SO) (which may need to be done through your supervisor). </li>
                                <li>The SO must sign off on any specific PI-submitted data access requests (DARs) which confirms your IC’s legal support for the PI to access the specific dataset. This is done for each separate dataset request.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </li>
                        <li>Prepare the Data Request
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li>Once your completed permission form is submitted and approved, you will be registered in the dbGaP system as an approved user and will be notified by email when you can proceed to submit data access requests to dbGaP.</li>
                                <li>Once you have access to the dbGaP access portal you will be able to view your research projects and ongoing requests.</li>
                                <li>Under “My Projects,” select “Create New Research Project.”</li>
                                <li>After reading the instructions and before you get started sections, select “Begin New Research Project.”</li>
                                <li>You can then search for HINTS data.</li>
                                <li>Click the checkbox next to “General Research Use” under the HINTS dataset label and press “Add Selected and Continue.”</li>
                                <li>You will then fill out various sections of the submission form, which include project title, research use statement, non-technical summary, signing official, internal collaborators, and IT director.</li>
                                <li>You will review data use certifications, restrictions on use, limitations on use, and various other documentation, then submit your application.</li>
                                <li>Once a data request is submitted, it is routed to your institution’s SO for review, approval, and co-signature.</li>
                                <li>For tips on preparing a submission, please visit this <a href="https://grants.nih.gov/sites/default/files/flmngr/Tips for Preparing a Successful DAR.pdf" target="_blank">dbGaP Tip Sheet</a>. </li>
                            </ol>
                        </li>
                        <li>A Data Access Committee (DAC) Reviews the Request
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li>Each dataset has a DAC, a group of experts who review the request for compliance with NIH policy and the appropriateness of the request with respect to the dataset.</li>
                                <li>If a request is approved, you will receive an email with additional instructions on accessing the dataset.</li>
                                <li>If a request is denied, you can adjust the submission and re-submit. There are <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/n/helpdbgap/DAreq_ReviseAmndUpd/#DAreq_ReviseAmndUpd.Revise_Data_Access_R" target="_blank">specific steps for resubmission</a>.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </li>
                        <li>Accessing the Data
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li>If a data request is approved via dbGaP, you will be referred to NCI’s General Commons to then access the data.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </li>
                    </ol>



                    <h2 id="AD_GC"><strong>Accessing Data via GC </strong></h2>
                    <p>A dbGaP data request must be approved prior to accessing data within the GC. For full and detailed instructions on how to access data within the GC system, visit the <a href="/docs/GeneralCommonsUserGuide.pdf" target="_blank">GC User Guide</a>.</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Once you are referred to the GC website, in the search bar, type in the name of the HINTS dataset you wish to download (or just search for HINTS and choose from the list).</li>
                        <li>You will see headers for "All" "Participants" etc. Click on "Studies"</li>
                        <li>Click on the Health Information National Trends Survey dataset you were approved to access.</li>
                        <li>Scroll down, and you will see all available files.</li>
                        <li>Click on which file you would like to add to your collection and then scroll to the bottom and on the bottom right, click "ADD SELECTED FILES."</li>
                        <li>At the top of the page, you will see a shopping cart with any files you selected. Click on the shopping cart.</li>
                        <li>In your shopping cart, there will be a button "AVAILABLE EXPORT OPTIONS" on the right side of the page. Click on this, and then click on "Export to Cancer Genomics Cloud."</li>
                        <li>You will then be prompted to sign in with your eRA Commons login.</li>
                        <li>If this is your first time signing into Cancer Genomics Cloud, you will need to fill in the user information, as well as read and click the Terms of Service and Privacy Policy before pressing "Proceed to the CGC."</li>
                        <li>You will then be prompted to choose a destination project. You may click "Create new project" and name it as you see fit. </li>
                        <li>You must read the usage information and click the "I understand…" button and then press import data. </li>
                        <li>Once data have been imported, you can toggle to "Projects" in the upper left hand. Click on the project you have created.</li>
                        <li>Next to "Dashboard" (upper left), you can click on "Files."</li>
                        <li>These are the HINTS data files you put into your cart and exported from steps 12-14.</li>
                        <li>Using the checkbox option on the left of each named data file, you may click and then copy, rename, move, download, and more.</li>
                    </ol>



